Yes, even today, many churches will drive DVDs or USB drives of services from their main location out to their other Some also are one week delayed at their remote Managing your video venues this way causes issues of disconnect, delayed teachings, and a sense of just watching TV at Utilizing the DVR based multisite church video delivery platform from FaithNetwork, your remote venues tap into real time services, viewing the live service from the main location seconds, minutes or even hours after it just Our solution allows you to encode an HD live stream from your main location to our hosted DVR recording You are then provided players to playback this DVR stream at your remote location or Multisite church has never been this easy! Providing Multisite Church Solutions Since Years ago, FaithNetwork was asked by one of our larger clients to help them launch their first video At the time, this was a very new and progressive Who would want to sit in church and watch a video of the service from across town? Well, we took the challenge and worked with then encoder company Kulabyte, now a division of Haivision, to develop a cloud based DVR solution for this mutual This launch was a great success! Due to high costs of Kulabyte and Haivision products we knew we needed to rework this system to be more cost effective so churches of all sizes could benefit from this We have evolved our systems over years of experience and that first customer is still streaming their video venues with They grew from 2 to remote campuses throughout the nation! LIBOR Transition Q&A | Market Alpha Intro About LIBOR Transition Webinar Replay LIBOR Transition Q&A Services Team Contact Us +1 (646) Intro About LIBOR Transition Webinar Replay LIBOR Transition Q&A Services Team Contact Us +1 (646) LIBOR Transition Q&A: Five Common Questions from the Market Alpha specializes in helping clients unpack complex aspects of market structure, which requires understanding the granular details along with an ability to tie data and information to strategic insights and As it relates to the LIBOR transition, Market Alpha can help clients in the following areas: • Governance Structure • Communication Strategy • Exposure Identification • Product Strategy • Contractual Remediation • Accounting, Tax and Regulatory Matters • Implementation and Conversion There is no issue facing the financial services industry that is more complex or daunting than the cessation of The challenges are just as significant for the as they are for dealers and At Market Alpha we frequently field questions from firms asking for advice on navigating the LIBOR Below are five of the most common… How will firms will be affected by the LIBOR transition over the next two years? The cessation of LIBOR represents a significant challenge for the Navigating this transition will affect firms in many The needs to understand that they now have a new risk in their portfolios – the fallback language in their Although the Fed is pushing for firms to convert their USD LIBOR positions to SOFR before the end of , there are many complicating LIBOR fallback language is highly inconsistent from one deal to the Even if a deal has fallback language for temporary disruptions in the setting of LIBOR, many do not anticipate a permanent This creates unintended consequences, including fallbacks that effectively turn a floating rate note to fixed at the last LIBOR setting if there are no banks willing to set a LIBOR Given the historically low level of LIBOR, this disincentivizes issuers to alter their fallback Another potential landmine for the is that some states require % consent in order to modify a This means that a single investor could hold up the conversion of a deal to an alternative reference rate if they do not give their consent to the new This is already happening 1 and has the potential to create a wave of litigation throughout the The cessation of LIBOR does not only affect certain parts of a It affects the entire organization – portfolio management, trading, marketing, operations, technology, risk management, The entire organization needs to be engaged in the process through a governance structure established by senior 1 See “CLO Libor fallback language proposal fails as investor balks at change” , https: www.reuters.com article clo-liborammcrefi clo-libor-fallback-language-proposal-fails-as-investor-balks-at-change-idUSL2N26S16P , Reuters, October 8, What should firms be focusing on now to prepare for the cessation of LIBOR? At this phase of the transition process we would advise firms to do the following: Establish a proper governance structure that will educate and empower the entire firm to deal with the LIBOR Identify and evaluate your firm’s LIBOR fallback Firm’s typically have a solid grasp on the basic details of their floating rate instruments – reset dates, maturity, spread, credit quality, However, when it comes to the LIBOR fallback language embedded in documents many firms do not know what will happen to deals if LIBOR fails to Understanding fallback risk is no easy task if a firm has thousands of deals tied to We recommend getting a handle on LIBOR fallback risk as soon as possible to identify problematic deals before they lose Investors may opt to sell rather than take the risk of an unfavorable outcome if LIBOR doesn’t Attempting to tackle the entire transition all at once is not Breaking the process down into discrete phases will help firms manage this very complex Create a plan that includes milestones and hold people accountable for meeting At this stage firms should not focus too much on the ultimate replacement SOFR is most likely going to be the alternative reference rate that many contracts convert to, but there is planty of time to focus on this after setting up a proper governance structure, identifying fallback risk and formulating a transition Market Alpha Advisors can help firms through every stage of the transition so do not hesitate to reach out if you need What can firms do now to address their LIBOR exposure in cash instruments (Bank Loans, Floating Rate Notes, MBS, ABS, Securitized Products, ) as part of their plan to transition away from LIBOR? REGIONAL GEOLOGIC SETTING The Auxer gold and silver project is located along a rich orogenic gold and silver belt that stretches from the Yukon to central This belt contains such world class orogenic districts as the mine and the Barkerville Auxer is located directly between the Sheep Creek orogenic gold camp in southern and the Murray gold district in Idaho, and shares many geologic characteristics of HOST ROCK The Auxer is hosted in a magnetite bearing quartz diorite This is the same host rock as the Bralorne block of the giant mine in (2.7 million ounces of gold at g t), and the same host rock as the giant West Branch deposit at the Tasiast gold mine in This rock has ideal characteristics to induce both chemical and physical depostion processes during an orogenic gold event, frequently resulting in both larger deposits and higher grades than competing host rock GEOCHEMISTRY The Auxer has rock chip gold grades of over 2 g t for over 2 km on the Historic and modern sampling of historic workings show significant intercepts of high grade material, up to feet g t (historic). COMPANY Under the direction of Jessie Jeanne Stinnett and award winning, , choreographer Itzik Galili, Boston Dance Theater (BDT) is Boston’s first contemporary dance repertory company with international ties at the leadership With a commitment to presenting works of relevance, BDT matches the talents of dancers with those of acclaimed global choreographers, broadening the scope of contemporary dance practice and performance in our BDT is a registered (c)3 charity as of OUR MISSION BDT s mission is to build and sustain a professional contemporary dance company dedicated to providing high quality dance performances, dance education and community outreach, to strengthen the dance community in Boston and create new dance BDT will accomplish this through partnerships with international and artists to create high quality work performed by local dancers, mentoring local choreographers and dancers, and by performing dance in performance locations, such as libraries, senior centers, art galleries and VISION, VALUES, HISTORY VISION In partnership with Global Arts Live and multiple community partners, BDT’s programs will grow to include Local Productions of no less than two public performances each year in the city of Boston, education activities and a trainee program for young dancers who one day aspire to dance within a professional company environment, and civic engagement events, bringing dance and poetry into public spaces via workshops and performance for young adults and Additionally, BDT seeks to build Partnerships with other community organizations in various reciprocal Presently, our active partnerships include: Boston Ballet School Newton who has hosted BDT as company in residence since , Hibernian Hall in Dudley Square who has hosted BDT s education programs since , Goethe Institut Boston in Back Bay, and the Israeli Consulate General to New VALUES We are interested in works which take risks by crossing cultural and interpersonal boundaries, and we engage artists whose artistic visions echo these As an organization dedicated to fostering cultural equity, we employ accessible creative process and conversation igniting product as conduits for disrupting opportunity gaps in our We aim to make contemporary dance available to historically underrepresented audiences both by connecting our international repertory to, and creating lasting relationships with respected, local cultural institutions, and holding low cost to no cost programming in underserved communities throughout Greater HISTORY Within the season, BDT appeared in performances at Jacob’s Pillow Inside Out, the Institute of Contemporary Art presented by Global Arts Live (formerly World Music CRASHarts), Salem State University, Israeli Consulate to New England, Emmanuel Music, New Movement Collaborative at Green Street Studios, Dance for World Community at Jose Mateo Ballet Theater, FOGXFLOW at the Emerald Necklace Conservancy, and Aeronaut Brewery sponsored by ​ BDT’s recent outreach activities include North Hill Retirement Community, Reading Public Library, Faneuil Branch of the Boston Public Library, Newton Senior Center, and Hibernian Hall in January will mark the sixth, Immersion Project welcoming local, national, and international dancers to Boston to study intensively and create new choreography with BDT company The DART series conferences highlight emerging challenges facing today’s global Respiratory viruses such as RSV and influenza virus are important threats to human health, especially in vulnerable populations such as infants, the elderly, and the The ongoing international distress around the pandemic warrants an , and platform where the latest developments and discoveries can be shared, discussed and RespiDART & Emerging Viruses strives to serve as one such platform by addressing unmet needs in knowledge dissemination and translation, highlighting the latest medical breakthroughs, translating bench science discoveries to real world clinical needs, and identifying current and future roadblocks on the path to successful vaccine and antiviral drug Considering recent seismic changes in global health as a result of the pandemic, RespiDART & Emerging Viruses will address an urgent and unprecedented need in global At the same time, this meeting will serve to highlight other emerging and viral threats such as chikungunya, norovirus, nipah, Dengue and yellow fever This year’s meeting will focus on topics such as advances in epidemiology, diagnostics, therapeutics, vaccinology, immunity and inflammation, virus host interactions, enzymology, and new study models in Emphasis is placed on sharing the latest clinical data for several small molecules advancing through human Novel drug targets and mechanisms of action will also be heavily Through participation in this event, delegates will be able to attend invited lectures by leaders, participate in several interactive panel discussions and take advantage of key networking opportunities included in the We hope to see you in December in sunny Los Cabos, or online, as we aim to make the program available in through the conference Program chair, Raymond Schinazi, PhD, DSc Emory University, USA Subscribe to the ihe newsletter Sign up with your email address to receive news and updates about upcoming Email Address Sign Up Thank you! FAQs - WellNested Skip to content Lactation Support Essential Care For Providers FAQs Lactation Support Essential Care For Providers FAQs FAQs Breastfeeding What types of issues topics can be addressed in a lactation consult? Expand Lactation consultant can address a number of topics in a visit, including: Prenatal counseling for breastfeeding Evaluating how much milk your baby is taking at each feeding session Examining infant position and latch Flagging (but not diagnosing) potential infant mouth issues such as , lip tie, and suggesting follow Helping address milk supply issues, n ipple pain, breast pain, and mastitis breastfeeding strategies to manage challenging situations such as mom and or baby medical conditions, preemies, or multiples Teaching about pumping and storag, w eaning, b ottle feeding Developing strategies for the return to work, including managing your supply and a pumping schedule What can I expect from a typical lactation consultant (LC) visit? Expand Initial visits typically last between Unless you’ve provided this information prior to the visit, the LC will ask you about you and your baby’s health, including your birth experience, prior breastfeeding experiences, and any underlying health For the baby, she’ll ask about: Weight at birth and weight checks since The number of wet and dry diapers daily Breastfeeding experience to date with this baby Any specific concerns you have During the visit, any or all of the following will occur: She’ll observe the baby’s physical appearance and behavior The LC will observe a feeding session She will weigh the baby before and after to assess milk intake (in the case of most and virtual plus visits). During virtual plus (with scales) visits, an LC will drop off a infant scale at your home to allow you to weigh the baby before and after a Purely virtual visits do not typically use Check baby’s latch, breathing, sucking and swallowing while feeding Correct positioning or any challenges she sees Give you written instructions or protocols to follow for feeding Refer you to any additional professionals to issues as needed Explain how to contact her for follow up questions and help What is the difference between an International Board Certified Lactation Consultant (IBCLC) and a Certified Lactation Consultant (CLC)? Expand An International Board Certified Lactation Consultant (often called an IBCLC) has accomplished the most rigorous breastfeeding training available, which includes: hours of lactation specific education health science courses - 1,000 clinical practice hours Successful completion of exam offered by an independent, international board of examiners IBCLS are often engaged to support the most challenging breastfeeding cases and are the only providers that insurance will reimburse Certified Lactation Counselors (CLCs) achieve their training through a number of different organizations, but training typically includes: Between - hours of classroom training Successful completion of a written exam offered by the training organization Some clinical shadowing may be completed as well Rates for CLC support are lower than IBCLCs and are not reimbursed by Mom Baby Nurse Care How were the nurses and other providers chosen? Expand The providers in our network were carefully vetted from an engaged group of passionate professionals who are eager to support parents outside of a hospital Many are mothers themselves, and deeply understand the importance of supporting empowering families in this special time of their All of our providers have been rigorously screened for professional experience in postpartum, labor & delivery and pediatrics from top accredited institutions and hospital In addition to having strong reputations in the local community, all providers have been background checked, have up to date vaccinations and have been interviewed for WellNested providers are sensitive, care deeply about supporting new families, believe in our mission to empower parents in their choices as well as remove burden from families so they can focus on enjoying this special moment in their For visits, what areas do you serve? Expand Currently, we are serving the Greater Boston area, including: Boston Arlington Belmont Cambridge Somerville Watertown Brookline Allston Brighton Newton Needham Wellesley Weston If you want to take part in WellNested care, and we do not currently serve your town, please reach out and we’ll see what we can do to support you! How is this different from what I’m getting from my pediatrician, OB GYN or hospital? Expand After delivery, your pediatrician will begin providing care tailored to your baby‘s needs within days of birth, but that won‘t include care for the birthing parent‘s physical or emotional Lactation support may or may not be offered , and the level of lactation training can vary widely by Your OB GYN office may with you after birth, but in most cases, no will occur until your visit (for ) or visit (for vaginal births) . Financing Patient Reviews Breast Reconstruction Breast Reconstruction Know Your Options Breast reconstruction surgery is plastic surgery which restores one or both of the breasts to their normal shape, appearance, symmetry and size following mastectomy, lumpectomy or other It is often performed in stages and can either begin at the time of mastectomy or be delayed until a later To make this procedure accessible to all our patients we provide Financing Call (414) for a cosmetic LEARN MORE Breast reconstruction generally falls into two categories: implant based or flap Implant reconstruction utilizes breast implants to help form a new breast Flap reconstruction uses the patient’s own tissue from another part of the body to form a new All our physicians at Illume Cosmetic Surgery are familiar with both approaches and will help guide you towards the option that best fits your needs and The surgeons of Illume Cosmetic Surgery have a close relationship with the ProHealth Waukesha Memorial Breast Center that has lasted over 2 decades with hundreds of breast reconstruction cases Chris Hussussian is currently the Chief of Surgery for ProHealth Waukesha leading the surgical department and working collaboratively with the physicians within Illume to provide the highest quality breast reconstruction in the Milwaukee After reconstruction, we partner with Rosie Good Ideas For the Taking - Ethos Giving WHAT WE DO OUR PEOPLE GOOD IDEAS RESOURCES NEWS CONTACT WHAT WE DO OUR PEOPLE GOOD IDEAS RESOURCES NEWS CONTACT Good Ideas For the Taking (GIFT) December , (Giving Tuesday) This Giving Tuesday, we are feeling inspired by Melinda Gates’ recent $1 billion pledge “to expand women’s power and influence in the United ” She rightly points out that gender equality is a vastly underfunded issue Setting women up to succeed in life and in leadership starts with supporting healthy, happy communities and raising strong, confident However, many of our institutions are failing to accomplish According to a KPMG Women’s Leadership Study , by adulthood, less than half of women personally identify with feeling confident despite recognizing confidence as a key leadership We need to reverse this confidence deficit to reach gender parity in So, how can funders make a greater impact in advancing gender equality? We have compiled our “good ideas for the taking” Female Participation in Sports Sports are a natural catalyst for leadership In fact, a joint study by EY and espnW found that % of women in executive level leadership played a sport while growing However, girls’ participation in sports is on the The Aspen Institute’s Project Play finds that girls are two to three times more likely than boys to drop out of sports between 8 th and th grades due to lack of access, prioritization of academics, and high costs of Funders can support female athletic programs by: Investing in female Subsidizing uniform, equipment, and transportation Creating dedicated play spaces for Sponsoring tickets for young athletes to attend professional women’s sports Providing academic support for female Supporting organizations that promote gender equality in sports like Play Like a Girl , Girls in the Game , Girls on the Run , and SheJumps . Female Representation in Fields We have established that there is a women’s leadership Worse, women are drastically outnumbered in several of the economy’s most dominant Females are underrepresented in these fields in part because our society unconsciously trains girls to associate certain activities with boys at an extremely early In a University of Washington study , the girls surveyed held stereotypes that boys are superior at programming and However, when given the opportunity to try these types of activities, the same girls exhibited similar levels of interest and for programming and robotics as Regardless of the associated gender stereotypes, girls should be exposed to a variety of activities when they are young and encouraged to continue pursuing their Funders can reduce gender stereotypes and expand female representation in fields by: Hosting workshops that teach parents how to model gender equality at Awarding “Equality Grants” to help teachers promote gender equality in their classrooms and sponsoring reading materials, games and lesson plans that reflect gender Offering test preparation, college guidance and career exploration resources to high school Supporting organizations that promote gender equality in STEM ( Girls Who Code , Built by Girls , DIY Girls ) and other activities ( WriteGirl , Girls Rock Camp Alliance , Girl Be Heard ). Female Mentorship Opportunities Quality mentorship is critical to women’s success and ascent to However, many mentoring programs are targeted toward women in the While these programs are beneficial, girls and young women often need support earlier on to help them enter the A study by Canada’s Centre for Addiction and Mental Health finds that girls who participate in formalized mentoring programs are more academically motivated, exhibit fewer behavioral problems and gain expanded professional Funders can facilitate effective mentorship programs and online by: Recruiting mentors from underrepresented fields and Facilitating trainings on successful mentoring Offering structured mentoring sessions that include guided conversations and shared Hosting professional development workshops for girls from local high schools and offering paid volunteer opportunities to female Supporting organizations that promote mentorship like Girls , Step Up , and Career Girls . Melinda Gates is right – gender equality can’t Let’s get to September , With the elections quickly approaching, everyone needs to be ready to We are all better off with a healthy democracy, and businesses play an essential role in promoting civic engagement in their employees, customers and In , % of nonvoters cited conflicts with work or school as the main reason for their lack of participation in the Fortunately, making voting as convenient as possible for your employees does not need to be Employers can directly increase voter participation by setting policies and doing their part to remind their employees of upcoming elections and It is important to remember that the right to vote is a civil right , and in many states, employers are required to provide employees with time to (You
